<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-210-924  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 210 924.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  April 1989 v109 n4 p69(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Systems integration and networking on the rise: optical disks as amass data storage medium have spawned document storage andretrieval systems.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Owens, Ben H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The last decade has seen much evolution in document managementtechnology.andP;  Electronic document management is a part of thelarger information revolution dominated by microcomputers andworkstations, and the availability of optical data disks aslow-cost mass data storage devices has produced a proliferation ofspecialized document storage and retrieval systems.andP;  Systems thatcapture, store and retrieve documents require special capabilitiesin workstations and networking: workstations need high resolutionmonitors and from two to eight Mbytes of RAM for image management;workstations must be able to compress and decompress raster imagedata; communications links must handle large packets of data athigh speeds; and a workstation must have a window open to onesystem while it receives and-or views document images on another.andO;Overall, electronic document systems are evolving towardworld-wide networked systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optical DisksStorage EquipmentMass MemoryInformation Storage and RetrievalDocument Management SystemsOffice AutomationOutlookIndustry Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>